  "opinion": "As a woman who grew up in a household where my father’s academic achievements were celebrated but my mother’s contributions were often overlooked, I’ve always been acutely aware of how societal expectations can shape our self-perception. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just a theoretical concept—it’s a lived reality for many who feel the weight of being perceived as ‘less capable’ in fields dominated by men. When I was a student, I remember sitting in a physics class where the teacher’s casual remark about ‘only boys being good at math’ made me question my own abilities. That moment, though small, echoed through my entire academic journey. In Bologna, where I’ve spent most of my life, I’ve seen how this phenomenon affects not just women but also people from minority backgrounds who face similar biases. The question of whether we should address it is clear: absolutely. But the way we do it matters. Instead of top-down interventions that might feel alienating, we need to build environments where every individual feels seen and valued for who they are, not just what they’re expected to be. For instance, mentorship programs that pair students with role models who share their backgrounds can foster confidence without reinforcing stereotypes. As someone who values quiet, thoughtful dialogue over loud debates, I believe the solution lies in subtle shifts in language and practice—like ensuring that classroom discussions include diverse perspectives and that teachers acknowledge the systemic barriers students face. It’s not about fixing people; it’s about creating spaces where everyone feels they belong. In the end, addressing stereotype threat isn’t just about improving STEM outcomes—it’s about honoring the dignity of every learner.",
